*   [United Express Flight 6291](/United_Express_Flight_6291), a flight operated by ACA for United that crashed.

On January 7, 1994, [United Express Flight 6291](/United_Express_Flight_6291) tragically crashed on approach to [Port Columbus International Airport](/John_Glenn_Columbus_International_Airport) (now [John Glenn Columbus International Airport](/John_Glenn_Columbus_International_Airport)) in [Columbus, Ohio](/Columbus,_Ohio). This flight, operated by Atlantic Coast Airlines, was utilizing a [British Aerospace Jetstream 41](/Jetstream_41) aircraft. The accident occurred during an instrument approach in icing conditions. The investigation by the [National Transportation Safety Board](/National_Transportation_Safety_Board) (NTSB) determined that the probable cause of the crash was the flight crew's failure to maintain adequate airspeed, leading to an aerodynamic stall. Contributing factors included the crew's failure to use the deicing system effectively and their delayed execution of a missed approach. All three crew members and two passengers perished in the accident, highlighting the inherent risks of aviation and the critical importance of adherence to flight procedures and weather protocols, especially for regional carriers operating smaller aircraft in challenging conditions. The incident served as a somber reminder of the responsibilities borne by regional airlines in ensuring safety standards comparable to their mainline partners.

